---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout title="Glossary">
  <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold mb-8 text-[#0A1628] dark:text-slate-100">Oligopeptide Glossary</h1>
  <p class="text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400 mb-8">
    Comprehensive terminology reference for oligopeptide chemistry, biology, and pharmacology.
  </p>

  <div class="space-y-6">
    <section>
      <h2
        class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-4 text-[#0A1628] dark:text-slate-100 border-b border-slate-200 dark:border-slate-800 pb-2"
      >
        A
      </h2>
      <dl class="space-y-4">
        <dt class="font-semibold text-[#0A1628] dark:text-slate-100">Amino Acid</dt>
        <dd class="text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400 ml-4">
          Organic molecule containing both an amino group (−NH₂) and a carboxyl group (−COOH). The
          20 standard amino acids are the building blocks of proteins and peptides.
        </dd>

        <dt class="font-semibold text-[#0A1628] dark:text-slate-100">
          Antimicrobial Peptide (AMP)
        </dt>
        <dd class="text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400 ml-4">
          Short peptides (5–50 aa) that kill or inhibit microorganisms. Part of the innate immune
          system. Examples: defensins, cathelicidins.
        </dd>
      </dl>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2
        class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-4 text-[#0A1628] dark:text-slate-100 border-b border-slate-200 dark:border-slate-800 pb-2"
      >
        P
      </h2>
      <dl class="space-y-4">
        <dt class="font-semibold text-[#0A1628] dark:text-slate-100">Peptide Bond</dt>
        <dd class="text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400 ml-4">
          Covalent amide bond formed between the α-carboxyl group of one amino acid and the α-amino
          group of another, with loss of water. Has partial double-bond character due to resonance.
        </dd>

        <dt class="font-semibold text-[#0A1628] dark:text-slate-100">Pharmacokinetics (PK)</dt>
        <dd class="text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400 ml-4">
          Study of drug absorption, distribution, metabolism, and excretion (ADME). Key parameters:
          half-life (t½), bioavailability (F), clearance (CL), volume of distribution (Vd).
        </dd>
      </dl>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2
        class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-4 text-[#0A1628] dark:text-slate-100 border-b border-slate-200 dark:border-slate-800 pb-2"
      >
        O
      </h2>
      <dl class="space-y-4">
        <dt class="font-semibold text-[#0A1628] dark:text-slate-100">Oligopeptide</dt>
        <dd class="text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400 ml-4">
          Peptide containing 2–20 amino acid residues. Distinguished from polypeptides (>20 aa) and
          proteins (>50 aa with defined tertiary structure).
        </dd>

        <dt class="font-semibold text-[#0A1628] dark:text-slate-100">Isoelectric Point (pI)</dt>
        <dd class="text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400 ml-4">
          pH at which a peptide carries no net electrical charge. Important for purification
          (isoelectric focusing) and formulation.
        </dd>
      </dl>
    </section>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
